d policies toward Asia for almost twenty years. This notion derived less from the reality of Chinese historical or cultural similarities than from a projection of American values and culture; in the American view, fueled by various political, economic, and religious interests, China was less a geographical entity than a symbol of American hopes and fears. One of the more important consequences was the idealization of China and the demonization of Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361593940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503615939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503615939/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles